    <statement><p>Find the <m>y</m>-intercept and any <m>x</m>-intercept(s) of the quadratic curve.</p>
<p><m>{y}={-x^{2}+16}</m></p>
<p><m>y</m>-intercept: <fillin characters="16" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p><m>x</m>-intercept(s): <fillin characters="17" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0,16\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(-4,0\right), \left(4,0\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>x=0</m> into <m>{y}={-x^{2}+16}</m>, and we have <m>y=16</m>.</p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,16)</m>.</p>
<p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>y=0</m> into <m>{y}={-x^{2}+16}</m>, and then solve for <m>x</m>.</p>
<p>For this problem, once we factor out the leading negative one, notice that the polynomial can be factored by the difference of squares formula:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = {-x^{2}+16} \\
   0 \amp = {-x^{2}+16} \\
   0 \amp = -(x^{2}-16) \\
   0 \amp = (x + 4)(x-4) \\
   x + 4 \amp = 0      \amp \text{or} \amp \amp  x-4 \amp = 0 \\
   x       \amp = -4  \amp \text{or} \amp \amp  x \amp = 4 
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercepts are <m>(-4,0)</m> and <m>(4,0)</m>.</p>
</solution>
